## Security Review — `app.js`

**Overall Risk: 🔴 CRITICAL — Not production-ready**

The application is a minimal Express.js server (23 lines). While its attack surface is small today, it is missing virtually every security control. Below are the findings ordered by severity.

---

### Finding 1 — No Authentication or Authorization
**OWASP A01:2021 – Broken Access Control | Severity: 🔴 Critical | Lines: 11–16**

Both `/health` and `/users` are publicly accessible with zero authentication. Anyone on the internet can call `/users` and enumerate user IDs, names, and emails.

**Fix — add JWT middleware:**
```javascript
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function authenticateToken(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers['authorization']?.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) return res.sendStatus(401);
  jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, (err, user) => {
    if (err) return res.sendStatus(403);
    req.user = user;
    next();
  });
}

// Apply to protected routes
app.get('/users', authenticateToken, (req, res) => { ... });
```

---

### Finding 2 — PII Exposed Without Access Control
**OWASP A01:2021 – Broken Access Control | Severity: 🔴 High | Lines: 12–15**

The `/users` response returns email addresses (PII) to any caller, which may violate GDPR/CCPA and enables phishing/credential-stuffing campaigns.

**Fix — role-based field filtering:**
```javascript
app.get('/users', authenticateToken, (req, res) => {
  const users = [
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob',   email: 'bob@example.com'   },
  ];
  // Only admins see email addresses
  const data = req.user.role === 'admin'
    ? users
    : users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name }));
  res.json(data);
});
```

---

### Finding 3 — No TLS / Plaintext HTTP
**OWASP A02:2021 – Cryptographic Failures | Severity: 🔴 High | Line: 18**

The server listens on plain HTTP. All traffic — including any future credentials or tokens — travels in cleartext, trivially intercepted on shared networks.

**Fix:**
```javascript
const https = require('https');
const fs    = require('fs');

https.createServer({
  key:  fs.readFileSync(process.env.TLS_KEY_PATH),
  cert: fs.readFileSync(process.env.TLS_CERT_PATH),
}, app).listen(443);

// Redirect HTTP → HTTPS in production
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (!req.secure && process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production')
    return res.redirect(301, `https://${req.headers.host}${req.url}`);
  next();
});
```
*(In Kubernetes/cloud, TLS termination at the load-balancer layer is also acceptable.)*

---

### Finding 4 — Missing Security Headers
**OWASP A05:2021 – Security Misconfiguration | Severity: 🔴 High | All routes**

No HTTP security headers are set. This leaves clients open to MIME sniffing, clickjacking, XSS, and MITM downgrades.

**Fix — drop in `helmet`:**
```javascript
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // sets X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options,
                   // HSTS, CSP, Referrer-Policy, and more
```

---

### Finding 5 — No Rate Limiting (DoS / Brute-Force)
**OWASP A05:2021 – Security Misconfiguration | Severity: 🔴 High | Lines: 7–16**

Unlimited requests are accepted. A single attacker can exhaust server resources or, once authentication is added, brute-force credentials.

**Fix:**
```javascript
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 min window
  max: 100,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
}));

// Tighter limit on sensitive endpoints
const strictLimiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 10 });
app.get('/users', strictLimiter, authenticateToken, handler);
```

---

### Finding 6 — CORS Not Configured
**OWASP A05:2021 – Security Misconfiguration | Severity: 🟡 Medium | All routes**

Without explicit CORS rules, browser-based cross-origin policies are left undefined. Once credentials are added, a malicious site could make authenticated cross-origin requests.

**Fix:**
```javascript
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://app.yourdomain.com'],
  methods: ['GET'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Authorization', 'Content-Type'],
  credentials: true,
}));
```

---

### Finding 7 — No Input Validation Middleware
**OWASP A03:2021 – Injection | Severity: 🟡 Medium | Lines: 1–16**

No body-parser size limit and no request validation exist. If write endpoints are added, the app will immediately be vulnerable to oversized payloads (JSON bomb), injection, and malformed data.

**Fix — add body limits now, validate when POST routes are added:**
```javascript
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));

// Example for future POST endpoint:
const { body, validationResult } = require('express-validator');

app.post('/users', [
  body('name').trim().notEmpty().isLength({ max: 100 }).escape(),
  body('email').isEmail().normalizeEmail(),
], (req, res) => {
  const errors = validationResult(req);
  if (!errors.isEmpty()) return res.status(400).json({ errors: errors.array() });
  // safe to proceed
});
```

---

### Finding 8 — No Error Handler (Stack Trace Leakage)
**OWASP A05:2021 – Security Misconfiguration | Severity: 🟡 Medium | All routes**

Express's default error handler prints stack traces in the response body in development and may leak sensitive internals in production.

**Fix — add a catch-all error handler as the last middleware:**
```javascript
// 404 handler
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});

// Global error handler — keep last
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log full error server-side
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'Internal server error'
      : err.message,          // dev only
  });
});
```

---

### Finding 9 — No Security Logging or Monitoring
**OWASP A09:2021 – Security Logging and Monitoring Failures | Severity: 🟡 Medium | All routes**

There is no request logging. Attacks (brute-force, enumeration, anomalous access) are completely invisible.

**Fix:**
```javascript
const morgan = require('morgan');

// Structured access log
app.use(morgan('combined'));

// Flag 4xx/5xx for security review
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.on('finish', () => {
    if (res.statusCode >= 400)
      console.warn({ ts: new Date(), method: req.method,
                     path: req.path, status: res.statusCode,
                     ip: req.ip });
  });
  next();
});
```

---

### Finding 10 — No CSRF Protection
**OWASP A01:2021 – Broken Access Control | Severity: 🟡 Medium | All routes**

Once session-based auth or state-mutating endpoints are introduced, the absence of CSRF tokens allows attackers to forge cross-origin requests on behalf of authenticated users.

**Fix (relevant once state-changing routes exist):**
```javascript
const csrf = require('csurf');
app.use(csrf({ cookie: { httpOnly: true, sameSite: 'strict' } }));

app.get('/csrf-token', (req, res) => res.json({ token: req.csrfToken() }));

app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  if (err.code === 'EBADCSRFTOKEN')
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid CSRF token' });
  next(err);
});
```

